35. Hind coxa: (0) evenly, densely microtrichose, as on meron, (1) microtrichia mostly absent, replaced by fine transverse sculpturing (
Fig. 15A–F
).

36. Hind coxa: (0) lacking anterior carina, with rounded fold only, (1) with narrow anterior carina (
Fig. 37A–F
).

The hind coxa in platypezids is cylindrical, plesiomorphic in its shape (
Fig. 37A
). The membranous part of the coxa posteriorly, the lumen, is long, facing posteriorly. Sciadocerines have the distal end of the coxa more slender (
Fig. 37B
), in some extension similar to 

Chonocephalus

or to 

Javanoxenia

(
Fig. 37C
). In some phorine genera (
Fig. 37D
), there is a carina, but it is not sharp or complete as in some other genera. The derived character state (
Fig. 37E, F
) apparently is convergent in higher metopinines and some phorines. Indeed, there are many more characters available in the modification of the hind coxa shape, but they are more subtle and are monophyletic for the main clades found here.

37. Halter: (0) elongate, large, (1) relatively small (
Fig. 26A–F
).

In outgroups (
Fig. 26A
), 
Sciadocerinae
(
Fig. 26B
), 
Chonocephalinae
(
Fig. 26C
), 
Termitoxeniinae
(
Fig. 26D
), basal metopinines and basal phorines, the halter is elongate and relatively large compared with the body size. In a group of genera the halter has become relatively small (
Fig. 26E, F
). This character is best defined in the most derived groups, such as hypocerines, and is somewhat intermediate in more basal groups (especially 

Beckerina

).

38. Limit between meron and anepimeron: (0) marked by suture (posterior arm of ‘W’), (1) without suture (
Fig. 38A–F
).

39. Surface of meron dorsally (and perhaps part of the anepimeron): (0) slightly convex or relatively flat, (1) deeply concave (
Fig. 39A–F
).

40. Posterior arm of anepimeron: (0) wide, (1) slender, compressed (
Fig. 40A–F
).

41. Ventral half of meron: (0) microtrichose, like upper half, (1) with microtrichia reduced or absent (
Fig. 41A–F
).

42. Dense setulae of scutum: (0) restricted to dorsum, (1) extending into lateral surface of thorax, especially over the anepisternum (
Fig. 42A–F
).

43. Anterior spiracle position: (0) below level of dorsal margin of anepisternum, (1) above level of dorsal margin of anepisternum (
Fig. 43A–F
).

44. Strong postpronotal seta: (0) present, (1) reduced, (2) absent (
Fig. 44A–F
).
